Exploring HotPot QA

A tutorial looking at HotPOT QA dataset and how it can be used to push Question Answering Systems

Jul 28, 2020 • 97 min read

jupyter   NLP   Q&A   Doc Intel

When you look at Squad Leaderboard, we are given an impression that problem of Question & Answering is solved. I mean a F1 score of 93.011 when compared to human performance(89.452), damn those are some impressive numbers. I am sure a media person might see those numbers and say we have machines which can beat humans at Question & Answering.

But Q&A is far from solved and that's the reason why we are getting datasets like MultiHopQA. I don't want to discuss about the fact that high performance on SQUad doesn't mean the best model on single paragraph question answering because datasets like TydiQa do talk about that a bit(Idea for next blog post ;)).

But let's look at another issue with Q&A models built on top of Squad. In every single case in Squad, we are answering question based on 1 single paragraph. But think of using the same Q&A model to get answers from a document.

Ouch we have ran into a problem now haven't we. To answer a question in a document, the model has to look at multiple places and our Squad trained model will have issues there.

Ps. I have used squad models on 100+ page documents and the model does well for certain type questions

And to address this problem, we have HotPotQA. Lets look at how HotPotQA differs from its peers

First, some datasets mainly focus on testing the ability of reasoning within a single paragraph or
document, or single-hop reasoning.*


TriviaQA (Joshi et al., 2017)and SearchQA (Dunn et al., 2017) create a more challenging setting by using information    retrieval to collect multiple documents to form the context given existing question-answer pairs. Nevertheless, most of the questions can be answered by matching the question with a few nearby sentences in one single paragraph, which is limited as it does not require more complex reasoning.

Third, all of the above datasets only provide distant supervision; i.e., the systems only know what
the answer is, but do not know what supporting facts lead to it

Once we have models solved for Second & Third problem, I am of the belief we are going to see a NLP boom in corporate firms. For everyone complaining about lack of explainibility the context of supporting information will be a welcome relief.

Well until then lets do a bit of exploration shall we?

Note- Anything in Italics is taken directly from the paper found here- https://nlp.stanford.edu/pubs/yang2018hotpotqa.pdf

So how did the authors collect such a challenging dataset?

Any dataset is only good as the technique they used for collecting dataset.

 The main goal of our work is to collect a diverse and explainable question answering dataset that requires multi-hop reasoning.

I am in all for the goal.

The overall setting is that given some context paragraphs (e.g., a few paragraphs, or the entire Web) and a question, 
a QA system answers the question by extracting a span of text from the context, similar to Rajpurkar et al. (2016). 
We additionally ensure that it is necessary to perform multi-hop reasoning to correctly answer the question.

So i short it seems, the dataset has a bunch of paragraphs for a question and to answer the question a system or model will need to look at multiple paragraphs.

In our pilot studies, we found that simply giving an arbitrary set of paragraphs to crowd workers is counterproductive, 
because for most paragraph sets, it is difficult to ask a meaningful multi-hop question. To address this challenge,
 we carefully design a pipeline to collect text-based multi-hop questions.

They seem to have given a lot of thought into what's the best way to collect data.

Building a Wikipedia Hyperlink Graph. We use the entire English Wikipedia dump as our corpus.
In this corpus, we make two observations:
(1) hyper-links in the Wikipedia articles often naturally entail a relation between two (already disambiguated) entities 
in the context, which could potentially be used to facilitate multi-hop reasoning;
 (2) the first paragraph of each article often contains much information that could be queried in a meaningful way. 
Based on these observations, we extract all the hyperlinks from the first paragraphs of all Wikipedia articles. With these hyperlinks, 
we build a directed graph G, where each edge (a, b) indicates there is a hyperlink from the first paragraph of article a to article b.

Their approach has to be to use Wikipedia to build a graph and that too in a very simple manner. They look at first paragraph of each article and looks at its hyperlinks and builds a graph where an edge represents there is an hyperlink between 2 paragraphs.

 Given an edge (a, b) in the hyperlink graph G, the entity of b can usually be viewed as a bridge entity that connects a and b.

I like where this is going. Its natural paragraph 'b' will be connected to paragraph 'a' because there is an hyperlink between both. But it shouldn't work for all cases right?

Entities like countries are frequently referred to in Wikipedia, but don’t necessarily have much in common with all incoming links.  It is also difficult, for instance, for the crowd workers to ask meaningful multihop questions about highly technical entities like the IPv4 protocol. To alleviate this issue, we constrain the bridge entities to a set of manually curated pages in Wikipedia

Manually curated pages should solve the above problem.

Comparison Questions. In addition to questions collected using bridge entities, we also collect another type of multi-hop questions—comparison questions. The main idea is that comparing two entities from the same category usually results in interesting multi-hop questions.
e.g., “Who has played for more NBA teams, Michael Jordan or Kobe Bryant?”

To increase the diversity of multi-hop questions, we also introduce a subset of yes/no questions
in comparison questions. This complements the original scope of comparison questions by offering new ways to require systems to reason over both paragraphs.

Who doesn't love diversity in a question answering dataset?

Collecting Supporting Facts. To enhance the explainability of question answering systems, we
want them to output a set of supporting facts necessary to arrive at the answer, when the answer
is generated. To this end, we also collect the sentences that determine the answers from crowd
workers.

Who doesn't like having a model explain how it came to a conclusion. Such a shame that we haven't more datasets like this which provokes the model to output the reason. I am not going to believe models are going to become less complex. And it is going to be very difficult to figure out the reasons for a decision based on poking the model's million parameters. But we could make the model tell us the reason for its decision na?

In all 3 levels, comparison questions seem to make up about 18-20% of the total training size.

Let's also look at the type of answers in the dataset.

This on first look, looks more diverse than Squad. But how come Yes/No only makes 6% wheen compared to around 18-20% comparison questions. This is because comparison questions contain scenarios like

"Who is better A or B?" as well as "Is A bigger than B?"

Note- Only the second type of questions can result in Yes/No. I sure as well like the diversity involved here.

Lets look at the reasoning which might be required to answer these questions.

Before we dive into the data lets look at the fields.

  1. _id: a unique id for this question-answer data point. This is useful for evaluation.
  2. question: a string.
  3. answer: a string. The test set does not have this key.
  4. supporting_facts: a list. Each entry in the list is a list with two elements [title, sent_id], where title denotes the title of the paragraph, and sent_id denotes the supporting fact's id (0-based) in this paragraph. The test set does not have this key.
  5. context: a list. Each entry is a paragraph, which is represented as a list with two elements [title, sentences] and sentences is a list of strings.
  6. type: either comparison or bridge, indicating the question type.
  7. level: one of easy, medium, and hard.

Now that's clear lets look at some samples.

Even with the supporting facts, its difficult to find the answer to that question.

Let's look at Test & Dev Set

The first thing to note about their dev & test set is that there are 2 benchmarks.

1) Distractor- Here they have taken 8 paragraphs from wikipedia using bigram tf-idf with the question as query and they mix it with 2 gold paragraphs.

2) Full Wiki- Here they test the model’s ability to locate relevant facts as well as reasoning about them by requiring it to answer the question given the first paragraphs of all Wikipedia articles without the gold paragraphs specified.

Full Wiki sure does look hard as hell. Lets look at each of them starting with the distractor setting first.

f = open('hotpot_dev_distractor_v1.json',)

I noticed that the questions are same across dev_wiki and dev_distractor with the only difference being the paragraphs. The authors claim the paragraphs in wiki setting were found using their retrieval system and they claim the correct gold paragraphs might or might not been in the list. This sure makes things interesting.

Let's try to see how many cases the gold paragraph is not there.

dev_wiki_df=pd.DataFrame(dev_wiki)
dev_wiki_df['matching_para_count']=''
for index,rows in dev_wiki_df.iterrows():

 
  context_paras=[]
  supporting_paras=[]
  for para_list in rows['context']:

    context_paras.append(para_list[0])
  
  for para_list in rows['supporting_facts']:
    # print (para_list[0])
    supporting_paras.append(para_list[0])
  supporting_paras=list(set(supporting_paras))
  count=0
  for item in supporting_paras:
    if item in context_paras:
      count+=1
  dev_wiki_df.loc[index, 'matching_para_count']=count

dev_wiki_df['matching_para_count'].value_counts()

1    4073
2    2089
0    1243
Name: matching_para_count, dtype: int64

Please forgive my shoddy loops. But seems they were right. Around 1243 pairs, there are no gold paragraphs. And in another 4073 cases there is only 1 gold paragraph.
